entry.title: AutofillProfile::origin deprecation: Importing logic.
entry.content:
This CL removes all form-importing related tests around verified

profiles. This distinction no longer exists.



Furthermore, it removes the distinction in

AutofillProfile::SaveAdditionalInfo(). As outlined in [1], this function

is only used in three places:

- The pre-Kustodie importing path, which is only used in unit tests at

this point [2] -> AutofillProfileComparator::MergeProfile() ->

AutofillProfile::SaveAdditionalInfo().

- Deduplication logic, for which the distinction was removed in

crrev.com/c/4502844.

- Billing address conversion logic, which is deprecated and about to

be removed. This logic doesn't have a concept of origin to begin with

since the billing addresses don't originate from Autofill [3].



Finally, the CL removes some of the final leftover (un)verified profile

related code/tests. These should all have been removed in a prior CL for

the specific functionality already, but were missed. See comments.

entry.title: [sync] Stop using IsSyncRequested for DISABLE_REASON_USER_CHOICE
entry.content:
A new approach is introduced, that leverages the state reported by

IdentityManager, when it comes to determining whether SyncService should

list DISABLE_REASON_USER_CHOICE among the reasons why sync-the-feature

is disabled.



The new logic is guarded with a kill switch but otherwise enabled by

default, as it is assumed that in practice both implementations should

be equivalent.



ChromeOS Ash is special-cased because there is a platform-specific

scenario where the sync-requested bit is needed. Namely, this is for

the case where the Sync server reports DISABLE_SYNC_ON_CLIENT (e.g.

data cleared via Sync dashboard).

entry.title: AutofillProfileSyncUtil: Deprecate origin
entry.content:
AutofillProfile::origin is being deprecated: The distinction between

verified and unverified profiles has already been removed, effectively

treating all profiles as unverified. A follow-up CL will remove the

origin from AutofillTable and the data model.



Older clients without these patches still distinguish between verified

and unverified profiles, however. In particular, the Sync bridge rejects

all updates from an unverified profile to a verified profile.

As to not break updates through Sync for old clients, whenever an

AutofillProfile is converted to AutofillProfileSpecifics for Sync,

this CL explicitly sets the origin of the specifics to kSettingsOrigin.

This ensures that older clients treat all incoming updates as verified

profiles and hence accept them.

By making them verified, older clients will exclude these profiles from

deduplication, etc. See doc linked in the bug for a discussion.



Note: ContactInfo doesn't have the concept of an origin, so it remains

unchanged.

entry.content:
This reverts commit 27c0797becaf3cb6ec5daaf3a97335c093328329.



Reason for revert: Seems it broke the ServiceWorkerRaceNetworkRequestBrowserTest* on https://ci.chromium.org/p/chromium/builders/ci/linux-bfcache-rel

Original change's description:

> [BestEffortServiceWorker] Use RaceNetworkRequest in the fallback case

>

> When the fetch handler result is a fallback,

> ServiceWorkerMainResourceLoader runs the fallback callback,

> ServiceWorkerSubresourceLoader creates another URLLoader, both classes

> dispatches additional network request to get responses.

>

> Currently RaceNetworkRequest doesn't intervene in this fallback process.

> This means the network request is dispatched twice (RaceNetworkRequest +

> fallback), or even three times (+ SW fetch handlers).

>

> This CL changes that behavior, not to dispatch the fallback request when

> RaceNetworkRequest is dispatched. Specifically, when the fetch handler

> response is a fallback, the browser notifies to

> RaceNetworkRequestURLLoaderClient to handle the response and ask to

> complete the commit instead of the fetch handler.

entry.title: [Jelly] Ensure legacy mappings correctly override target variables.
entry.content:
A previous CL (http://crrev/c/4495886) accidentally broke legacy

mappings by making the legacy mappings key be treated as a variable

declaration. This meant they got prefixed with the current

namespace and were passed through the variable reference to css var

transforms. This results in legacy mappings that did not override

their respective css vars.



After fixing this i did some more diligent testing and discovered a variety of issues, this cl addresses all of the issues I found:

* Updates legacy mappings to take in raw css vars as keys + updates

tests to make this bug more obvious in the golden updates.

* Ensures the generated css vars for legacy mapping values are also

unscoped via a hack to `CSSColorVar`. A more optimal solution

would be to make `CSSColorVar` only produce a result from the

`color` value, however this is a more involved change and left for

a follow up.

* Removes self references in light/dark legacy mappings. The

previous solution referenced css vars cyclically causing the

variables to be dropped entirely by the browser.

* Dumps legacy mapping in both the default selector and the dark

mode selector to ensure variables are always overridden.

Previously css vars defined in the dark mode selector were

winning against our legacy mappings since they had higher

specificity.

* Updates `UPDATE_GOLDENS` to false since it was accidentally

committed as true.

entry.title: [WebUI] Migrate MediaAppUI to WebUIConfig
entry.content:
Context:

Currently WebUI properties, e.g. CSPs, requesting schemes, host, mojo,

etc. are stored in WebUIControllers themselves or in separate lists

like IsWebUIAllowedToMakeNetworkRequests. The lifetime of a

WebUIController is bound to the frame, which makes it hard to use for

some use cases where the WebUIController hasn't been created yet. A

non-dynamically allocated class where clients could query a WebUI's

properties would be easier to use and audit.



WebUIConfig is a class that stores properties of WebUIs. For now the

properties are 1. the WebUI's origin, 2. if the WebUI is enabled,

and 3. GetURLDataSource() method for service worker initialization.

In the future this class could include information like CSPs, if we

should enable Mojo, if we should enable chrome.send(), if we should

allow network requests, URLDataSource, etc.

entry.title: [WebUI] Migrate TrustedProjectorUI to WebUIConfig
entry.content:
Context:

Currently WebUI properties, e.g. CSPs, requesting schemes, host, mojo,

etc. are stored in WebUIControllers themselves or in separate lists

like IsWebUIAllowedToMakeNetworkRequests. The lifetime of a

WebUIController is bound to the frame, which makes it hard to use for

some use cases where the WebUIController hasn't been created yet. A

non-dynamically allocated class where clients could query a WebUI's

properties would be easier to use and audit.



WebUIConfig is a class that stores properties of WebUIs. For now the

properties are 1. the WebUI's origin, 2. if the WebUI is enabled,

and 3. GetURLDataSource() method for service worker initialization.

In the future this class could include information like CSPs, if we

should enable Mojo, if we should enable chrome.send(), if we should

allow network requests, URLDataSource, etc.

entry.title: [BestEffortServiceWorker] Use RaceNetworkRequest in the fallback case
entry.content:
When the fetch handler result is a fallback,

ServiceWorkerMainResourceLoader runs the fallback callback,

ServiceWorkerSubresourceLoader creates another URLLoader, both classes

dispatches additional network request to get responses.



Currently RaceNetworkRequest doesn't intervene in this fallback process.

This means the network request is dispatched twice (RaceNetworkRequest +

fallback), or even three times (+ SW fetch handlers).



This CL changes that behavior, not to dispatch the fallback request when

RaceNetworkRequest is dispatched. Specifically, when the fetch handler

response is a fallback, the browser notifies to

RaceNetworkRequestURLLoaderClient to handle the response and ask to

complete the commit instead of the fetch handler.
